default15.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe believe that 
defaultthe
default 
defaultdisproportionate adverse effect 
defaultof a residence test 
defaulton non UK nationals may amount to unlawful discrimination. It 
defaultis likely to be unlawful under s29 of the Equali
defaultty Act
default 2010
default, which prohibits discrimination in the provision of services including those provided by public authorities.
default If 
defaultthe residence test amounts to unlawful discrimination on the ground of nationality, there is no statutory defence
default in the Equality Act
default.
default&#xa0;
default15.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt may be discriminatory under Article 14 
default(prohibition of discrimination) 
defaultcombined with Article 6 
default(right to a fair trial) 
defaultof the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR)
default. Article 14 requires that there should be no unjustified 
defaultdiff
defaulterence of 
defaulttreatment between people who are similarly placed in relation to rights guaranteed by the Convention. As 
defaultlegal aid is only available for matters of English law 
defaultfor proceedings before domestic courts it is difficult to see how residence status can
default be a 
defaultlegal 
defaultbasis for distinguishing
default between people
default for the purpose of legal aid eligibility.
default Article 1 requires states to secure Convention rights to 'everyone within their jurisdiction'.
default&#xa0;
default15.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA change of this nature interferes with the common law rights 
defaultof access to the 
defaultcourts and non discrimination.
default&#xa0;
default According to 
defaultthe now well-established common 
defaultlaw principle of legality, the general words of the power to make regulations in LASPO are not apt to allow such a fundamental interference with constitutional ri
defaultghts, which can only be effected by primary legislation.
default&#xa0;
default15.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt may also fall foul of EU prohibitions of discrimination on grounds of nationality and EU law provisions such as Article 47 of the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights which provides that legal aid sh
defaultall be made available to those who lack sufficient resources to ensure effective access to justice in relation to the implementation of EU law.  It may also be contrary, depending on the circumstances of the case, to legal aid provisions under Council Dire
defaultctive 2002/8/EC which provides that persons involved in cross border disputes are entitled to appropriate legal aid to obtain effective access to justice. Article 4 of the Directive 
defaultstates that legal aid must be made available without discrimination to EU 
defaultcitizens and third country nationals residing lawfully in a member state. The 12 month qualification rule is incompatible with this provision.
